	  <title>Example: A Linear Map from a Matrix</title>
	  <caption>Example: A Linear Map from a Matrix</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>The matrix</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>A = \left[\begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array}\right]</latex>
			      </math.display>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>is of size <math>
                  <latex>(2,1)</latex>
               </math>. Therefore it determines a linear map <math>
                  <latex>L\from \RNr[1] \to \RNr[2]</latex>
               </math>, namely</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>L(x) = \left[\begin{array}{c} 2 \\ 1 \end{array}\right]\cdot [x] = \left[\begin{array}{c} 2x \\ x \end{array}\right]</latex>
			      </math.display>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>Thus <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> sends a <math>
                  <latex>1</latex>
               </math>-tuple <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}=(x)</latex>
               </math> to the coordinate pair <math>
                  <latex>(2x,x)</latex>
               </math>. Now investigate the transformation properties of <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>We investigate the transformation properties of <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> by evaluating it on some small integers</para.body>
               </para>
			
			            <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img src="ims/LinearTrafo2To1.png"/>
               </media>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>So we see that <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> transforms the line 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>
                        </hot>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>This is the domain of <math>
                                    <latex>L</latex>
                                 </math>
                              </para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </subordinate>
				on the left into the 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>green line</hot>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The green line is the image of <math>
                                    <latex>L</latex>
                                 </math>.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </subordinate>
				on the right. If we look more carefully, we can notice that in the process <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> gets stretched by a factor of <math>
                        <latex>\sqrt{5}</latex>
                     </math>. How do we see this? Each interval of length <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> is transformed into the hypothenuse of the right triangle with edges of length <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math>. </para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>The matrix</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>
					
A = \left[
\begin{array}{rr}
0 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 0
\end{array}\right]
					
				</latex>
			      </math.display>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>has size <math>
                  <latex>(2,2)</latex>
               </math>. So it determines a linear transformation <math>
                  <latex>R\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex>
               </math>, namely</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>
					
R(x,y) = \left[
\begin{array}{rr}
0 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 0
\end{array}\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
x \\ y
\end{array}\right] =
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
-y \\ x
\end{array}\right]
					
				</latex>
			      </math.display>
			
			      <para>
            <para.body>In other words, if <math>
                  <latex>(x,y)\in\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math> is arbitrary, then <math>
                  <latex>R(x,y)=(-y,x)</latex>
               </math>. Now investigate the transformation properties of <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> by applying it to pairs <math>
                  <latex>(x,y)</latex>
               </math> where <math>
                  <latex>x,y</latex>
               </math> are small integers.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>We investigate the transformation properties of <math>
                        <latex>R</latex>
                     </math> by evaluating it on pairs of small integers</para.body>
               </para>
			            <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img src="ims/Rotation90.png"/>
               </media>
			
			            <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>R(1,0)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(0,1)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>R(0,1)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(-1,0)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Inspection of these 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>sample points</hot>
                        <info>
						                     <para>
                              <para.body>To confirm this impression, go ahead and compute the effect of <math>
                                    <latex>R</latex>
                                 </math> on some more sample points, e.g. <math>
                                    <latex>(-1,0),(0,-1),(1,1),(-1,1)</latex>
                                 </math>, etc.</para.body>
                           </para>
					                   </info>
                     </subordinate>
				
				suggests that <math>
                        <latex>R</latex>
                     </math> transforms the plane <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> by rotating it counter clockwise through the angle of  90 degrees. This is, indeed, the case as we will learn later on.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
